Date: Wed, 27 Sep 2000 09:08:01 +0300
From: Shamsudeen Fagbo <oloungbo@zajil.net>
Source: Arab News, Wed 27 Sep 2000 [edited

Rift Valley Fever Death Toll Reaches 33 in Saudi Arabia
-------------------------------------------------------
JIZAN: Agriculture and Water Minister Abdullah ibn Muammar has been camping
in Jizan ever since Rift Valley Fever was discovered in the region. He has
been conducting daily inspections, holding meetings with the local
community, and monitoring the work of the disease-fighting teams.
The death toll from the viral disease increased to 33 yesterday, a Health
Ministry official said. The number of people affected by the virus had risen
to 160, he said, adding that 30 of them have recovered and left hospitals.
The minister said that 18 planes would join the fight against the
potentially fatal disease on Thu 28 Sep 2000 in such a way that even heavy
rainfall could not hamper the teams activities. The minister said a special
committee would estimate the number of cattle killed by the disease before
the cause of the death was identified. There are statistics, however. on the
number of deaths after the disease was diagnosed (about 11 600).
Compensation will be paid on the basis of prevailing market rates, the
minister said.
With the help of experts from South Africa the source of the disease will be
pinpointed in the next 10 days so that potentially dangerous locations can
be isolated. Currently the team is collecting samples from diseased and dead
animals. Spraying operations to exterminate mosquitoes are also continuing
unabated. Muammar said South African experts had found that a considerable
number of villages had not been affected by the disease. All healthy cattle
in these regions will be vaccinated against the disease in order to avert
the possibility of it recurring. The minister also gave assurances about
fool-proof plans to eradicate mosquitoes in the region. Aerial sprays and
manual spraying around farms and houses were being undertaken all the time,
he said. The minister also confirmed that diseased animals would be killed
with the help of experts in such a way that the operation would not
adversely affect nearby towns or people. The ministry has been co-operating
with the Ministry of Health to find out how the disease is transmitted to
humans, he added.
Muammar also said special arrangements would be made to stop the smuggling
of disease-ridden animals from Jizan to other regions. All entry points will
be watched carefully and aerial reconnaissance will be carried out. Several
attempts to smuggle out animals from Jizan had already been detected and
stopped,he added. The minister revealed that the spraying of insecticides
was being undertaken by 5 planes specially designed for such work. Eight
helicopters and several planes will be added to intensify the operations,
which will continue for at least 3 months.
--
Shamsudeen Fagbo
<oloungbo@zajil.net>
