Date: Tue, 26 Sep 2000 21:00:39 +0100
From: Nick Honhold <nick@plewland.demon.co.uk>

Possibility of Further Spread of Rift Valley Fever?
---------------------------------------------------
The arrival of Rift Valley fever (RVF) in the Middle East is clearly very
worrying, especially for those countries. I would raise one other worry.
Another viral disease of livestock has moved from Africa to the Middle East
in recent years, i.e. Peste des Petits Ruminants (PPR). This virus has since
moved on to South Asia i.e. India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Nepal. What are the
chances that RVF could follow this route if it isn't eradicated from Saudi
Arabia and the Yemen? Were it to do so, the outcome would probably be a
disaster on a large scale. So this move by RVF may have much greater
implications in the future and should spark a serious international response
to eradicate it from Saudi Arabia and the Yemen.
--
Nick Honhold
<nick@plewland.demon.co.uk>
[A significant epidemiological difference between RFV and PPR is that the
former is caused by an arthropod-borne bunyavirus, whereas PPR is caused by
a predominantly aerosol-transmitted paramyxovirus. However, if illegal
smuggling of stock is a factor in spread of these diseases, this difference
would not be relevant. - Mod.CP
